\begin_layout Standard
In this writeup,
 I work with a new notion:
 
\shape italic
modules
\shape default
.
 Formally,
 a module is a set of tasks that represented by the same time cost parameters.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is to simplify the notation—
specifically,
 to represent tasks that form AI chains collectively as blocks with one set of cost parameter,
 similar to human tasks.
 It helps avoid tracking which task(s) within the AI chain are automated and which are augmented.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A module is either a manual task (i.e.,
 each singleton set of manual tasks is a module) or an AI chain (i.e.,
 a set of tasks grouped together and represented by a composite cost parameter).
 Any module belongs either to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

,
 the set of tasks that are performed manually by human,
 or to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{A}$
\end_inset

,
 the set of AI chains.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea behind introducing modules is to treat AI chains similar to tasks,
 with their own cost parameters and bypass the notational complexity arising from tracking which task(s) in the chain are automated and which task is augmented.
 In the rest of the document I refer to manual tasks as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tasks
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and AI chains as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

modules,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but I might also use the two terms interchangeably wherever the context is clear.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Hierarchical Production Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the following hierarchical model of production.
 The smallest building block in the economy is a task/module denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 One or more tasks are combined into a job,
 a bigger building block of production denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 An industry (or sector),
 denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

,
 is formed by combining a bundle of jobs as the next production block in the hierarchy.
 Finally,
 goods from different sectors are combined together to produce a single final good in the economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we ignore how goods from different sectors 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\{1,\cdots,K\}$
\end_inset

 are combined to create the unique final good.
 Also,
 we focus on a single sector and drop the industry index 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 for the ease of notation in the remainder of the writeup.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are only two levels of production in the economy:
 1) tasks to jobs,
 2) jobs to sector.
 We assume production at each level is Leontief:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Tasks to Jobs:
 Leontief with module 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 taking 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 time to complete.
 If done manually,
 task 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 takes time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}^{H}$
\end_inset

 and if done with AI,
 module 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 takes (expected) time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}^{AI}\alpha^{-d_{i}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the difficulty parameter of the AI chain.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{j}=\min\left(\min_{h\in\mathcal{H}_{j}}\ \frac{l_{h}^{H}}{z_{h}\ t_{h}^{H}},\ \min_{a\in\mathcal{A}_{j}}\ \frac{l_{a}^{AI}}{z_{a}\ t_{a}^{AI}}\right)\label{eq:task_job}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 is the output produced by job 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 We refer to 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

intermediate good 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Jobs to Industry:
 Leontief with all jobs contributing equally to production of industry good:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x=min(x_{1},\cdots,x_{J}).\label{eq:job_ind}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the industry good,
 and the second level of aggregation (from jobs to industry) is merely a technical assumption imposed to show that all jobs must be done once in order to produce the industry good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Have in mind that the wage rate at job 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 is fixed and equals:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{j}=v_{L}+\sum_{h\in\mathcal{H}_{j}}c_{h}^{H}+\sum_{a\in\mathcal{A}_{j}}c_{a}^{AI}.\label{eq:job_wage}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


