\begin_layout Plain Layout
Two Types of Heterogeneity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There are two ways to incorporate heterogeneity into the model:
 at the task level 
\bar under
or
\bar default
 the job level.
 Below,
 I briefly discuss the implications of each approach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Job-level heterogeneity:

\series default
 Here,
 tasks have fixed durations across firms—
i.e.,
 all firms share the same 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}^{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}^{AI}$
\end_inset

 for a given task/module 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 For example,
 the task of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Writing a Report
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 takes the same amount of time for all firms,
 regardless of the context or environment.
 What differs among firms is the contribution of jobs—
specifically,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 parameter in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:job_ind"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

—
to industry-level production.
 For instance,
 firm 1 might use 2 units of intermediate good 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 1 unit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j_{2}}$
\end_inset

 (thus 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}=2,b_{2}=1$
\end_inset

) to produce one unit of the industry good,
 whereas firm 2 might require 5 units of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 1 unit of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j_{2}}$
\end_inset

 for the same output (thus 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1}=5,b_{2}=1$
\end_inset

) .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Task-level heterogeneity:

\series default
 In this case,
 tasks do not have fixed durations—
i.e.,
 different firms have different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}^{H}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}^{AI}$
\end_inset

 for the same task/module 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 For example,
 the task of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Writing a Report
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 might take longer for firm 1 than for firm 2 in the same context (some firms are just better at writing reports).
 Despite this variation in task durations,
 a job composed of the same set of tasks contributes equally to the production of the industry good across firms.
 This means that while the 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

s vary across firms,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

s (which determine the contribution of jobs to industry good production) remain the same for a given job design.
 For simplicity,
 we can normalize 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

s to be 1 across all jobs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The difference that the choice of heterogeneity type makes is the form of input that goes into the aggregated CES function:
 while the job-level heterogeneity yields a CES function in terms of job wage bills 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{j}t_{j}$
\end_inset

 (i.e.,
 Equation 
